                                                    <figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Optimal Sets & Reps of Dumbbell Hammer Curl                                                    </figcaption>
                                                </figure>
                                            </div>
                                                                        </div>
                                                                                                                                                            <div class="content-item bd-bot exercise-list-start">
                                    <h2 class="title-content">How to Put in Your Workout Split</h2>
                                    <p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The dumbbell hammer curl is a variation of the traditional bicep curl. It allows for better targeting of the </span><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC10054060/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener"><span style="font-weight: 400;">brachialis muscle</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">, which is deeper than the biceps. This means you can include both exercises in your programming to achieve strong arms.</span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">This exercise can be incorporated in many different ways, from helping you bounce back after injury to gaining overall upper-body strength. Here are a few options to try:</span></p><ul><li>Arm day â€“ Include this exercise on any basic arm day. Opt for hammer curls, bicep curls, tricep pushdowns, and tricep extensions for a balanced approach.</li><li>Push-pull â€“ If you break your workouts down into push, pull, and legs, the hammer curls fit seamlessly into the pull day. Perform it alongside deadlifts, rows, lat pulldowns, and other arm curls.</li><li>Circuit training â€“ For those with endurance goals, hammer curls may be a great addition to interval or circuit training.</li><li>Full-body â€“ Hammer curls are also an excellent option for full-body days. They can be performed alongside squats, bench presses, rows, and more.</li></ul><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Hammer curls can also be programmed as part of supersets. Supersets are where you alternate between opposing muscle groups, perfoming one after the other.</span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">For example, you could alternate between performing hammer curls and tricep pushdowns to save time. This can also be another great option for boosting overall endurance.Â </span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">If youâ€™re interested in increasing arm strength, consider performing hammer curls at the beginning of your workout. In contrast, if youâ€™re goal is hypertrophy, add these curls to the middle or end of your program after compound movements.</span></p>                                                                    </div>
